    <title>Scientists who built ‘foundation’ for AI awarded Nobel Prize</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A man stands at a podium" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/BCXqBDa1gJDgWLWxFTHVY3-1Cmw=/0x0:4596x3064/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73639489/1260013125.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;Geoffrey Hinton, called the “Godfather of AI,” during day Collision 2023 at Enercare Centre in Toronto, Canada.&lt;/em&gt; | Photo By Ramsey Cardy / Sportsfile for Collision via Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="h3bSfS"&gt;Two scientists credited with laying the “foundation of today’s powerful machine learning,” University of Toronto professor emeritus Geoffrey Hinton and Princeton University professor John Hopfield, were &lt;a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2024/press-release/"&gt;awarded the Nobel Prize in physics&lt;/a&gt; today.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="Ss4L0j"&gt;Their discoveries and inventions laid the groundwork for many of the recent breakthroughs in artificial intelligence, the Nobel committee at the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences said. Since the 1980s, their work has enabled the creation of artificial &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24201441/ai-terminology-explained-humans"&gt;neural networks&lt;/a&gt;, computer architecture loosely modeled after the structure of the brain. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="EY8Ead"&gt;By mimicking the way our brains make connections, neural networks allow AI tools to essentially “&lt;a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2024/popular-information/"&gt;learn by example&lt;/a&gt;.” Developers can train an artificial neural...&lt;/p&gt;
